    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin confusion earlier. Let's clear up the math behind your student loan amortization table. The amount of your monthly payment is divided into two parts: the interest and the principal. The interest for each month is calculated by multiplying the remaining balance of the loan by the monthly interest rate. The formula for the interest portion of your payment is:\n\nInterest = Remaining Balance x Monthly Interest Rate\n\nThe principal portion of your payment is then the total monthly payment minus the interest portion. The formula for the principal portion is:\n\nPrincipal = Total Monthly Payment - Interest\n\nAs you continue to make payments, the interest portion decreases, and the principal portion increases, but this happens gradually. The exact amount of interest and principal in each payment depends on the remaining balance of the loan and the interest rate. If you're seeing little movement in your principal balance, it could be because the interest portion of your payment is still quite large compared to the principal portion. Over time, as the balance decreases, the interest portion will also decrease, and you'll start to see more of your payment going towards the principal. I hope this clears up the math for you!",
